---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Testing" description="Verify FactFeed with pytest, API testing, error states, and CI results.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Testing</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">In Project 1, testing meant Lighthouse and a real phone. FactFeed has a backend, a database, and a worker — now testing means automated tests that prove the system works.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">AI writes the tests. You validate they cover the acceptance criteria from the requirements.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">What to verify</h2>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">pytest results</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The CI pipeline runs pytest on every PR. Before deployment, check that all tests pass:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>All unit tests pass (models, utilities, data validation)</li>
    <li>All integration tests pass (API endpoints hit the real database)</li>
    <li>No skipped or xfail tests hiding real failures</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">API testing</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">With Docker running locally, test the API manually:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">/api/health</code> returns <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">{'{"status": "ok"}'}</code></li>
    <li><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">/api/facts</code> returns facts from the database</li>
    <li>Invalid requests return proper error responses (not 500s)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Error states</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">What happens when things break? Verify the app handles failures gracefully:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>If the database is unreachable, does the API return a clear error?</li>
    <li>If the external facts API is down, does the worker fail gracefully?</li>
    <li>If the frontend can't reach the backend, does it show an error state?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">CI results</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Check the GitHub Actions tab on your repository. Every PR should show:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Green check on the CI pipeline</li>
    <li>Tests ran and passed (not skipped)</li>
    <li>Lint checks passed</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>The AI-first shift:</strong> AI generates test cases and writes the test code. Your job is checking that the tests actually cover the acceptance criteria — not just that they pass. A test suite that only tests the happy path is worse than no tests, because it gives false confidence.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: testing tools & strategies</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">pytest is one of many testing tools. Here's what else exists across languages and testing strategies.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">pytest</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Python's dominant testing framework. Fixtures, parametrization, plugins. Covers unit, integration, and API testing.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Jest</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">JavaScript testing framework by Meta. The default for React projects. Snapshot testing, mocking, code coverage.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Vitest</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Newer, faster alternative to Jest. Built for Vite projects. Compatible API, faster execution. Growing rapidly.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Playwright</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Browser automation by Microsoft. Opens real browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari), automates clicks and form fills, takes screenshots. We'll introduce this in Project 4 for end-to-end testing.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Cypress</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Alternative to Playwright. Excellent developer experience, time-travel debugging. Playwright handles more browsers and is more flexible; Cypress has a gentler learning curve.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Postman</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">API testing tool with a visual interface. Send requests, organize them into collections, share with your team. Good for exploring APIs during development.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">k6 / Locust</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Load testing tools. Simulate thousands of users hitting your API simultaneously. We'll introduce load testing in Project 8.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Coverage reports (pytest-cov, istanbul)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Measure how much of your code is tested. We'll enforce coverage thresholds in CI from Project 3 onwards.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Testing tools vary by language and framework, but the strategy is universal: unit tests for individual functions, integration tests for service interactions, end-to-end tests for user flows. The pyramid stays the same — only the tools change.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: deploy to staging</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Tests pass. Time to ship the full stack to a live URL.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/2/deployment"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Deployment →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
